Market Commentary
Investing can be a challenging yet rewarding process. Information changes rapidly which is why it is so important to stay informed. Please enjoy our latest market commentary.


Second Quarter Market ReviewJuly 5, 2017 | Print ViewThe beat goes on.  The first quarter set the tone for the market, the second quarter carried out the now familiar tune.  The stock market hits new record highs only to be followed by more record levels.  This should be a euphoric time for investors where bull markets typically end in tragedy.  Instead, investors remain overly cautious expecting something disastrous at any moment.  The longer investor nervousness continues, the longer this bull market will run.

The economic data fully supports the bull market.  The political and social headlines are successfully distracting investors from what really matters; corporate earnings.  The stock market is celebrating a strong first quarter of corporate earnings and earnings estimates for the second quarter look even better.  Add to this; low unemployment rates, stable interest rates, benign inflation and most of all a healthy consumer and we have a recipe for record breaking days on Wall Street.

Stock returns were positive around the globe in the second quarter as emerging markets and international developed stocks outperformed U.S. stocks.  International markets are in the midst of a solid run, offsetting some recently troubled years.  A recent acceleration in overseas economic growth and compelling valuations is being reflected in international stock prices.  The U.S. market had been riding the technology wave through early June when the tide turned for a brief moment.  Growth stocks are crushing value stock investing in the first half of the year. Energy has been the primary laggard as oil prices found their way to the low end of a recent $40-$60 a barrel range.

A widely anticipated Federal Reserve rate hike came as advertised after their mid-June meeting.  The Federal Reserve is on a quarterly mission to raise short-term interest rates and return to a normal monetary policy.  The Fed funds target rate now sits at 1.00-1.25%.  In addition to adjusting monetary policy, the Fed also must reduce their inflated balance sheet by selling trillions of bonds they purchased during the multiple post financial crisis quantitative easing programs.  This process will begin later this year and will take years to unwind.  Expect relative stability in bonds as rates remain low, but inch higher over time.

The 10-year U.S. Treasury finished the quarter with a 2.29% yield after reaching a low yield for the year of 2.12% in June. The yield curve continues to flatten as the short end reacts to the Fed rate hikes and the long end celebrates low inflation. Credit spreads are locked in at the tightest levels of the year thanks to the strong equity market and a healthy risk appetite from investors.  Investment grade spreads and high yield spreads remain very tight, helping these sectors outperform the overall bond market.

Interest rates are low, stock prices are high and this scenario will likely continue well into the third quarter.  Stock prices will be supported by a new round of earning releases which comes on the heels of the best earnings quarter since 2011.  Expect more good news on this front.  With credit spreads tight and interest rates low don’t expect too much from bonds in the second half of 2017.  The first half of the year has exceeded our fixed income return expectations, so flat returns in the second half would be a win.  Stocks should continue to ride high on the corporate earnings train.

